The mean \( \mu = p = 0.25 \) and the variance \( \sigma^2 = \frac{p(1-p)}{n} = \frac{0.25 \times 0.75}{500} = \frac{0.1875}{500} = 0.000375 \).  
Given \( d = 0.05 \), \( d^2 = 0.0025 \), and \( \frac{\sigma^2}{d^2} = \frac{0.000375}{0.0025} = 0.15 \).  
By Chebyshev's inequality, \( P\left(\left| \frac{Y}{n} - 0.25 \right| < 0.05\right) \geq 1 - 0.15 = 0.85 \).  

