Solution: The probability of drawing a white chip, \(P(W)\), is calculated using the law of total probability. The probabilities of selecting each bowl and the conditional probabilities of drawing a white chip given the selected bowl are as follows:

- \(P(B_1) = \frac{1}{2}\), \(P(W \mid B_1) = 1\) (since bowl \(B_1\) has two white chips).
- \(P(B_2) = \frac{1}{4}\), \(P(W \mid B_2) = 0\) (since bowl \(B_2\) has two red chips, no white).
- \(P(B_3) = \frac{1}{8}\), \(P(W \mid B_3) = \frac{2}{4} = 0.5\) (since bowl \(B_3\) has two white and two red chips).
- \(P(B_4) = \frac{1}{8}\), \(P(W \mid B_4) = \frac{3}{4} = 0.75\) (since bowl \(B_4\) has three white and one red chip).

Thus,  
\[
P(W) = (1 \times 0.5) + (0 \times 0.25) + (0.5 \times 0.125) + (0.75 \times 0.125).
