Problem: Calculate the magnitude of the spin angular momentum of a proton. Give a numerical answer.  The unit of the answer should be  $10^{-35} \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~s}$.
Solution: The magnitude of the spin angular momentum of a proton is given by \( S = \sqrt{s(s+1)}  \hbar \), where \( s = \frac{1}{2} \) is the spin quantum number. Substituting the values, \( S = \sqrt{\frac{1}{2} \left( \frac{1}{2} + 1 \right)}  \hbar = \sqrt{\frac{3}{4}}  \hbar = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}  \hbar \).

Using the reduced Planck constant \( \hbar \approx 1.0545718 \times 10^{-34}  \text{J} \cdot \text{s} \) and \( \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \approx 0.866025403784 \), the calculation yields:
\[
S \approx 0.866025403784 \times 1.0545718 \times 10^{-34} \approx 9.13286 \times 10^{-35}  \text{J} \cdot \text{s}.
\]

The result is expressed in units of \( 10^{-35}  \text{J} \cdot \text{s} \), so the numerical value is approximately 9.13286. Rounded to three significant figures, this is 9.13.

