Problem: The ${ }^7 \mathrm{Li}^1 \mathrm{H}$ ground electronic state has $D_0=2.4287 \mathrm{eV}, \nu_e / c=1405.65 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$, and $\nu_e x_e / c=23.20 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$, where $c$ is the speed of light. (These last two quantities are usually designated $\omega_e$ and $\omega_e x_e$ in the literature.) Calculate $D_e$ for ${ }^7 \mathrm{Li}^1 \mathrm{H}$. The unit of the answer should be  $\mathrm{eV}$.
Solution: The dissociation energy from the bottom of the potential well, \( D_e \), is related to the dissociation energy from the zero-point level, \( D_0 \), by the formula:

\[ D_e = D_0 + \frac{1}{2} \omega_e - \frac{1}{4} \omega_e x_e \]

where \( \omega_e = \nu_e / c = 1405.65  \text{cm}^{-1} \) and \( \omega_e x_e = \nu_e x_e / c = 23.20  \text{cm}^{-1} \).

First, calculate the zero-point energy (ZPE) in cm⁻¹:

\[ \frac{1}{2} \omega_e = \frac{1}{2} \times 1405.65 = 702.825  \text{cm}^{-1} \]

\[ \frac{1}{4} \omega_e x_e = \frac{1}{4} \times 23.20 = 5.80  \text{cm}^{-1} \]

\[ \text{ZPE} = 702.825 - 5.80 = 697.025  \text{cm}^{-1} \]

Convert ZPE from cm⁻¹ to eV using the conversion factor \( 1  \text{cm}^{-1} = 1.23984193 \times 10^{-4}  \text{eV} \):

\[ \text{ZPE} = 697.025 \times 1.23984193 \times 10^{-4} = 0.0864201  \text{eV} \]

Now, add ZPE to \( D_0 = 2.4287  \text{eV} \):

\[ D_e = 2.4287 + 0.0864201 = 2.5151201  \text{eV} \]

Rounding to four decimal places (consistent with the precision of \( D_0 \)) gives \( 2.5151  \text{eV} \).

